# Programming Rules

1. Don't apply these rules blindly, think beforehand.
2. Don't trust developers or agents, developers make mistakes all the time either by using your code or by using their code.
4. When writing code, think that worst programmer in the world is going to use your code, is that person going to be able to use your code without making mistakes?
5. When writing code, if you think the best programmer in the world is going to read your code, what would that person think about your code?
6. Write code that won't surprise the reader. Re-read your code and think if someone would find it surprising.
7. Pay attention to details.
8. Always handle errors (fail fast), since languages came out, developers got used to ignoring errors and now there's a whole industry arround capturing unhandled errors. Expected ways to handle errors include:
    1. Return the error to the caller of the function
    2. Log the error: We need to know what's going on when things start failing in production otherwise we will have a bad time trying to find the root of the issue
    3. Retry the operation
    4. Perform a fallback operation
9. Prefer very explicit code and behavior over implicit one.
10. When in doubt, prefer restrictive over permissive policies. It's always easier to open than to close.
11. Review codebase before any new implementation, could simplify more things than expected.
11. Keep cognitive load very low.
12. Always validate and clean up user input.
13. Retry operations that depend on the network.
14. Write future-proof code, not code for next week.
15. Write extensible code.
15. Use comments to explain Why, not How or What.
16. Write short functions with one single purpose.
16. Never write files longer than 300 LOC, else single responsability gets lost
17. Always think about what can go wrong with your code, be creative
18. Keep reading multiple times your code while writing it.
19. Always be consistent with the rest of the code.
20. Keep code flat and avoid nesting blocks when possible.
21. Prefer returning functions early over long blocks.
22. Prefer readable, maintainable code over performance.
23. Before writing code/algorithms, first design the input data structures and the output data structures.
23. There's always more than 1 solution to a problem, and generally the first one you find is not good.
24. Never trust the user/system input.
25. If you are taking too much time solving a problem, go back to the input data and check if you are missing information.
26. When debugging an issue, separate facts from assumptions and verify assumption by assumption to see whether it's true or not.
27. Optimize for common cases and not rare ones.
28. Avoid magic numbers in the code. Use constants with explicit names.
29. Choose progress over perfection, everything that we do can be better so perfection doesn't exist and trying to achieve only delays or stops progress.
31. The backend should not trust their clients AT ALL.
32. The clients (Frontend, mobile apps, etc…) trust the backend but not completely, it should be paranoid and be prepared for failures.
33. Add spaces between blocks of related code, but formating is always welcomed.
34. Do not share variables that are accessed by multiple threads (unless they are thread-safe)
35. When designing, always have a single source of truth for your data.
36. In HTTP don't return 5xx unless there's something really broken.
37. Think about how your code is going to run in other environments, not just your computer.
38. Global variables are dangerous, avoid them unless you have a strong reason and you know exactly what you're doing.
39. Don't change/assign global variables within a thread unless the variable is thread-safe.
40. Don't expose global variables to other packages unless you know exactly what you're doing.
41. If you decide to use a global variable make sure the name and everything suggests that it should not be changed.
42. Only use global variables when the alternative is too “expensive”, always consider an alternative solution and its cost.
43. Don't duplicate code within the same context. It's ok to duplicate it in different contexts.
45. If you're gonna use a string that can change or you're going to use more than once then use a constant
46. Only use short variable names in short functions
47. When writing code, think what's the worst thing that could happen if someone misuses your code? How much money is going to be lost? How much information is the hacker going to be able to gather when my code is hacked?

## Python guidelines

1. Always use imports on top of file, never inside functions or classes
2. Keep functions short -> Refactor if grows in complexity
3. Prefer early returns